Thanks for the comments.

Skip is spot on. I should have explained more. The great Richard
Trevithick was a Cornish engineer, the first to experiment with high
pressure steam, making engines much smaller and more efficient. This
one dates from 1804. It was a static engine which he built for an
ironworks in South Wales, where he had the idea of putting it on
wheels and running it on the tramway. So this was the world's first
steam railway locomotive. It worked fine, the only problem was that
the iron tracks broke under the weight of the engine, so the idea was
abandoned!

And John, the model is entirely of thin card, (except for some 3mm
wooden dowel for axles and shafts). It's a very clever design. The
gear wheels have a central wheel, around which is wrapped a rim,
slotted to fit over the teeth. Then a long strip goes around the rim,
folded to go up and over each tooth. Then the two sides are added.
There's a sample free download on the designers site of one of the
gear wheels.

Roger
